The merge request widget is starting to get a bit cluttered and can feel overwhelming to use. With this effort we should design and architect a way for other teams to easily add in new extensions as long as the data matches what we specify.

## Design

Currently we have widgets like the below screenshot, they include a short summary and an expand button to see more information.

![Screenshot_2020-08-12_at_09.58.26](/uploads/fdda5d8a4211328390d7c22cc2859070/Screenshot_2020-08-12_at_09.58.26.png)

Can we somehow re-design this to make the widget feel less cluttered and overwhelming? :shrug: 

## Architecture

This is the bit where it gets a bit more complex. We need to decide on way that allows for other teams to give us the data structures that we decide. 

1 thought for this could be treat these extensions as plugins. Each plugin **must** match a set structure that we decide, the widget can then take these plugins, iterate and then render the data provided.

```javascript
const testSummaryPlugin = {
  request() {
    return this.$apollo.query({...});
  },
  summary() {
    return 'Test summary contained no changed test results out of 126144 total tests';
  },
  expansion() {
    // Return maybe an array that we can iterate and render?
  },
};

mergeRequestWidget.register(testSummaryPlugin);
```

(the above is just a super simple spaghetti code idea)

It would also be good if the summary could maybe request a small subset of data so that we aren't request a lot of data for each part until the user explicitly expands that area.

This will be a cross team effort to get each part matching what we expect. But the overall outcome means that teams can easily add in parts to the merge request widget as long as matches what we (~"group::source code"), who owns the widget, design.

